  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a global consensus that money laundering is against the law.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **International Treaties and Conventions:** Numerous international treaties and conventions, such as the United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (Vienna Convention), the United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (Palermo Convention), and the International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism, require signatory nations to criminalize money laundering.\n\n*   **National Laws:** Virtually every country in the world has enacted laws that specifically prohibit money laundering. These laws vary in detail and scope but share the common goal of making it illegal to conceal or disguise the proceeds of crime.\n\n*   **Intergovernmental Organizations:** Organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) set international standards to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. Member countries are expected to implement these standards in their national laws.\n\n*   **Public Opinion:** There is a widespread public understanding that money laundering is wrong because it facilitates criminal activities and undermines the integrity of financial systems.\n\nIn short, the illegality of money laundering is a widely accepted principle enshrined in international agreements and national legislation worldwide.",
